The recommender system made unsuitable recommendation. 
 Its reasons are as follows: Extracted preferences and dislikes:
- Preferences: intimate late‑80s R&B/pop traits (warm midrange lead vocals, emotionally direct storytelling, immediate memorable hooks), warm sax and clean guitar fills, concise radio‑friendly arrangements, tight cohesive sequencing for repeat plays; singer‑centered adult‑contemporary production with tasteful strings/piano when they serve the song, clear well‑balanced mixes, warm analog tones, tasteful acoustic guitar, tight harmonies, singable choruses and present, forward vocals. Danceable is acceptable so long as tracks remain concise.
- Dislikes: glossy, overlayered productions that bury the vocal (especially extended disco/funk grooves and dense percussion stacks), synth‑forward angular new‑wave textures, and hushed, reverb‑heavy minimalism that reduces vocal presence.
Why the polished adult‑contemporary set (CD2) is the best match:
- Direct match to core vocal and arrangement preferences: CD2 explicitly lists warm midrange lead vocals, emotionally direct storytelling, tasteful strings/piano, clean guitar and sax touches, and singable hooks. Those items are the central elements I described as primary priorities (warm midrange voice, sax/guitar accents, tasteful strings/piano used to serve the song).
- Production and sequencing fit my listening habits: CD2 mentions warm analog mastering, concise radio‑friendly arrangements, and tight sequencing—exactly the production values I prefer (analog warmth and concise, repeatable track lengths rather than extended grooves). Tight sequencing and concise arrangements increase replayability, which I emphasized.
- Avoidance of disliked traits: CD2’s description stresses intimacy and vocal‑forward presentation rather than glossy layering, extended dance grooves, or synth‑forward textures. That aligns with my dislike of productions that bury the vocal or prioritize groove length over immediacy.
Why I reject Ultimate Hits: Rock And Roll Never Forgets (CD1):
